{
  "card_id": "candle_3_continuation",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Candle 3 Continuation",
  "aliases": [
    "C3",
    "C3 Continuation",
    "c3 continuation",
    "Candle 3",
    "candle 3 extension",
    "Candle 3 Extension",
    "continuation candle",
    "Continuation Candle",
    "continuation expansion candle",
    "Continuation Expansion Candle",
    "continuation K-line",
    "Directional Candle",
    "Distribution Candle",
    "Expansion Candle"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "In the fractal model, the expansion candle following a Candle 2 reversal. It opens with a shallow opposing wick, then expands directionally with a small wick and large body, delivering the distribution phase aligned with the higher time frame bias, often after a change in state of delivery (CISD). Preferred over the reversal candle for trading.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Candle 2 must close as a reversal candle that sweeps a prior high/low and closes back inside its range, preferably preceded by accumulation (Candle 1).",
    "On the lower time frame, Candle 3 opens with a shallow opposing run (wick) early in its time period.",
    "A change in state of delivery (CISD) occurs during the opening wick, forming a protected swing.",
    "After CISD, Candle 3 expands directionally with a small wick, large body, and a close near its extreme, delivering an open-high-low-close (or open-low-high-close) sequence aligned with bias.",
    "The setup must align directionally with the daily/higher time frame bias and target relevant liquidity draws (e.g., previous day high/low, failure swings).",
    "If Candle 3 closes back over the CISD or opposing candle level, the continuation is invalidated.",
    "Candle 3's wick must be shallow and not cross the 50% level of the previous candle's wick; crossing 50% indicates the wick is disrespected.",
    "The opposing run should occupy only a small proportion of the candle's time period.",
    "The setup should form at key higher time frame levels (e.g., FVG, swing highs/lows) to increase validity.",
    "Optional: Confirm with Order Block formation or Fair Value Gap retest on lower time frame.",
    "Optional: On lower time frame, look for Change in the State of Delivery (CISD) confirmation."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Candle 3 is the primary tradeable candle after a Candle 2 reversal. Enter on the lower time frame after the Candle 3 wick forms and CISD confirms a protected swing. Stop below the protected swing; target minimum 2R, standard deviation projections, or HTF liquidity. Time frame alignment increases confluence; reduce targets if HTF does not support expansion. Trade the body, not the wick.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Trading the Candle 2 reversal candle directly instead of waiting for Candle 3 to form.",
    "Trying to catch/chase the wick instead of waiting for it to form, leading to repeated stop-outs.",
    "Trading continuation after price closes back over the CISD level, which invalidates the setup.",
    "Trading counter-bias setups inside a HTF Candle 3 zone, which tend to fail immediately.",
    "Entering on a candle that does not support expansion (e.g., large opposing wick, open-high-low-close structure).",
    "Looking for shallow opposing run entries late in the candle after a large range has already formed.",
    "Projecting far standard deviation targets when the opposing run is large, instead of scaling to -1 SD.",
    "Fighting an active expansion candle to trade back into the range rather than waiting for a new reversal.",
    "Trading a lower time frame Candle 3 without checking that the higher time frame candle also supports expansion in the same direction.",
    "Expecting a full expansion move when the HTF candle is a reversal candle, instead of taking conservative targets toward the daily open.",
    "Failing to wait for a clear CISD on a lower time frame within Candle 3.",
    "Not confirming Candle 2 closure at HTF key levels, leading to false signals.",
    "Confusing Candle 3 closure with Candle 3 continuation – Candle 3 must close strongly beyond Candle 2's opposite extreme to expect Candle 4 continuation.",
    "Ignoring the equilibrium point (0.5) – if Candle 3 fails to respect Candle 2's 0.5 level, the pattern may fail.",
    "Continuing to follow the pattern beyond Candle 4, potentially entering a new price phase.",
    "Entering before Candle 2 fully closes and reversal is confirmed.",
    "Confusing Continuation Candle with Expansion Candle, leading to mistimed trades.",
    "Ignoring wick size importance – trading continuation after a large wick candle increases risk of being stopped out.",
    "Trading Candle 3 after Candle 2 has already expanded significantly, as the available range is consumed.",
    "Holding through consolidation or counter-expansion in Candle 3 instead of waiting for a new signal.",
    "Misidentifying any large body candle as an Expansion Candle without checking the 50% wick rule.",
    "Trading Expansion Candle without an established HTF bias.",
    "Confusing large wick candles with Expansion Candle – large wicks indicate opposing run, not expansion."
  ],
